<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1261,1286]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The combination of a unique valva, phallus with remarkable set of cornuti, and a brown-black forewing with silvery markings (
<figureCitation box="[518,614,1297,1322]" captionStart="FIGURES 126 – 131" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,206,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[154,1432,193,1887]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 126 – 131. Holotype of Hesperolyra robinsoni Stonis, sp. nov. 126, male adult, holotype (idealized); 127 – 129, male genitalia, capsule with phallus removed, genitalia slide no. 29122 (BMNH); 130, 131, same, phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583364/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 126</figureCitation>
) distinguishes 
<taxonomicName box="[782,923,1297,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Hesperolyra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robinsoni" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[782,923,1297,1321]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">H. robinsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[930,1019,1297,1322]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[930,1019,1297,1322]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
from all other congeneric species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1333,1358]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[276,375,1333,1358]" captionStart="FIGURES 126 – 131" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,206,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[154,1432,193,1887]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 126 – 131. Holotype of Hesperolyra robinsoni Stonis, sp. nov. 126, male adult, holotype (idealized); 127 – 129, male genitalia, capsule with phallus removed, genitalia slide no. 29122 (BMNH); 130, 131, same, phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583364/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 126</figureCitation>
). Documented in 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[577,892,1333,1358]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson, 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 26, 
<figureCitation box="[946,1029,1333,1358]" captionStart="FIGURES 44 – 48" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[153,1433,193,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[153,1433,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 44 – 48. Stigmella unicaudata Remeikis &amp; Stonis, sp. nov. 44, female genitalia, paratype, slide no. RA 314; 45, same, slide no. RA 313; 46 – 48, leaf-mines on Azara microphylla Hook. f. (Salicaceae) (ZMUC)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583350/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
. Forewing about 
<quantity box="[1227,1316,1334,1358]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
, wingspan about 
<quantity box="[225,319,1370,1394]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="4.2">4.2 mm</quantity>
. Head: palpi cream; frontal tuft pale ochre; collar ill-defined, cream; eye-caps cream; antenna unknown. Thorax and tegula brownish black. Forewing brownish black with golden gloss and little purple iridescence, and with a few silvery markings on forewing; fringe grey with some long lamellar wing scales overlapping fringe; forewing underside cream brown. Hindwing brownish cream; fringe pale brow, with no androconia. Abdomen ochre brown on upper side, ochreous cream on underside; genital segments ochreous cream, not contrasting in color with ventral surface of abdomen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" box="[199,418,1585,1610]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1585,1610]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,370,1621,1646]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[384,543,1621,1646]" captionStart="FIGURES 126 – 131" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,206,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[154,1432,193,1887]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 126 – 131. Holotype of Hesperolyra robinsoni Stonis, sp. nov. 126, male adult, holotype (idealized); 127 – 129, male genitalia, capsule with phallus removed, genitalia slide no. 29122 (BMNH); 130, 131, same, phallus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583364/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figs 127–131</figureCitation>
). Description was provided in 
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[887,1198,1621,1646]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson, 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 44. Capsule 310 µm long. Phallus 130–154 µm long;, 45–65 µm wide; vesica with numerous large spine-like and plate-like cornuti.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" box="[199,886,1693,1718]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,1693,1718]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Bionomics</emphasis>
. Adults fly in April. Otherwise biology unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,987,1729,1754]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" box="[199,987,1729,1754]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1729,1754]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[360,426,1729,1754]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1986,2008]" captionTargetBox="[182,1401,510,1932]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[182,1401,509,1961]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution map to the species treated in the current paper." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583342/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). This species occurs in tropical forests of 
<collectingRegion box="[908,983,1729,1754]" country="Belize" name="Belize" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<collectingCountry box="[908,983,1729,1754]" name="Belize" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Belize</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1765,1790]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after the late Gaden S. Robinson, an outstanding taxonomist, co-author of the first review of the Neotropical 
<taxonomicName box="[538,684,1801,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Nepticulidae</taxonomicName>
, our former colleague and dear friend.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1436,1189,1898]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1837,1862]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species was discovered by J. R. Stonis (formerly R. Puplesis) and G. S. Robinson, but left unnamed and documented as 
<taxonomicName box="[482,580,1874,1897]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Fomoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[482,580,1874,1897]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fomoria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species 
<quantity box="[675,774,1873,1898]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.396988" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="in" value="29122.0">29122 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Puplesis" box="[781,1084,1873,1898]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" refString="Puplesis, R. &amp; Robinson, G. S. (2000) A review of the Central and South American Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to Belize. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum, London (Entomology), 69 (1), 1 - 114." type="journal article" year="2000">Puplesis &amp; Robinson 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 44.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
